post_text:
When District 89 had to cancel in-person classes due to the COVID-19 pandemic students, teachers, administrators and the school community were left wondering how, when or if our lives would return to normal. Yet, through these difficult times instruction continued in District 89 via Zoom, Microsoft Teams, YouTube and other creative means to keep our students engaged. We also continued to feed our students and to date we have distributed over 220,000 meals.
The #D89Community is a strong one and we remain committed to serving our families.

post_text:
Unable to host end-of-the-year music concerts, the D89 Music staff collaborated with fellow teachers and administrators to record this virtual music performance as a tribute to our students and community. The song “From Now On” (from the Greatest Showman) was chosen for its powerful lyrics which speak of “returning home…” and “remember(ing) who all this was for….”

We will return home, and we will make music together again.
#D89Community

School District 89 added 38 new photos from February — at Irving Middle School.
March 3 at 3:18 PM ·

On Thursday, February 27, 2020, Irving Middle School hosted D89’s Family Night: Black History – Music through the Ages. Families throughout the District traveled through time as they witnessed performances from each school highlighting different genres.
As an extra special treat, Irving Showstoppers sang a beautiful rendition of ‘Life Every Voice’ and Maywood Fine Arts performed “Iceberg.” Thank you to all our community partners for joining us at such a fun event.

shared_text:
Melrose Park Elementary School
February 28 at 2:37 PM ·

As a culmination to Black History Month, The 4th graders created an interactive listening wall of songs by Scott Joplin, the “King of Ragtime.” Mustangs browsed the gallery to listen to the songs and learn more about his achievements in Ragtime.

Mrs. Williams’ 5th grade class performed a Ragtime dance at the D89 Family Night – Black History Celebration at Irving Middle School.

The Mustang Leaders hosted an interactive assembly to recognize and appreciate how some of the things we use every day were invented by African Americans.
During the Mustang Daily Announcements, students read passages that highlighted influential African Americans.

shared_text:
School District 89
November 1, 2018 at 12:27 PM ·

November is National Family Literacy Month and the 1st of November marks National Family Literacy Day. Remember that reading each and everyday is part of your student's homework. We ask that everyone read at least 20 minutes a day and you can see by the chart that it makes a huge difference in student test scores.

Set aside time in the evening to read together. #D89Reads

Garfield School hosted D89's Family Night: Literacy Pumpkin Patch and it was a smashing success! Families enjoyed a book character fashion show, giveaways, and fall treats.

Each school had a decorated pumpkin representing a book and attendees voted for their favorite. Congratulations to Lincoln School for winning best pumpkin!

As an extra special treat, students interviewed author Victoria Watkins!

Thank you to all of our community partners for joining us on such a fun night.

post_text: Our Wildcats not only move their bodies in PE, but use their minds as well. Thanks Mr. Schammert for building our #D89BrightFutures!
shared_text:
Washington Dual Language Academy
October 18, 2019 at 10:16 AM ·

A BIG Friday shout out to our very own Mr. Schammert for keeping our Wildcats engaged in such a fun way during Physical Education! Wildcats practiced their underhand toss with a game called "Make it, Stack it". As Wildcats make buckets with their underhand toss they get to stack them up. If they miss, they hand the ball to the next player for another try. The goal of the game is to stack six buckets! Kudos to Mr. Schammert for being such a cool P.E. teacher! #D89Bilingual #D89WIldcatsRoar
